이나영님과 비슷하긴한데, 방탄님들 한참 인기가 터졌을 때(?) 애 낳고 정신없는 와중에 누군진 모르고 노래만 들었는데, 애기 조금 크고 월드 클래스라며 난리가 나니까 뭐야 해서 봤더니 '아 그 때 들었던 노래들이 방탄노래였구나' 했다가 개개인 방송들 보니까 개개인이 참 인간적으로 너무 멋져서 인간 대 인간으로 참 멋지고 어떤 부분들은 존경스럽다까지 느껴지더라구요ㅎㅎ나이가 조금이라도 어리면 '동생' 이라고 생각하고 대다수 그랬는데 오빠라고 부르고 싶을 정도로 배울 부분이 많아요! 근데 애기가 커서 6살이 돼서 이래저래 삼촌들 멋져? 했는데 연관을 어찌했는지 핸드폰 보여주면 "dynamic"보면서 삼촌들 멋있어~하고 있네요.

무튼 새로운 역사를 쓴 BTS가 멤버들이 원하는 그 "이상" 호호할아버지가 될 때 까지 BTS이길 바라고 그렇게 되실 거 같구 그렇게 될 수 있을 거 같아요 

정말 드라마나 티비랑 다 안보지만 흥은 있어 당시 힙한 노래는 잘 듣는데, 흠...너무 길게 적어 더 말하긴 그렇지만, 정말 유일무이하고 전무후무하게 서로를 위하는 거 같고 노력하시고 본인을 받아들여서 나아가시는 그 모습이 멋져요~ 항상 화이팅

text:
It's interesting how Suga has developed as host. In the beginning Suga is trying his best to break the ice, make her laugh and ease the tension as she seems quite quiet, introverted, mellow melancholic person. Suga keeps on counting similarities and giving her confidence to talk by answering his questions himself at first. The way Suga keeps on being honest, comfy, soft with her, after first half she starts vibing along. At last when she opens up about losing her dog, the way he sympathizes and then talks about how everybody have different healing process.
His genuineness. His Softness.
All in all I'm in love with Yoongi the human. 💜😌

author: @usarmyblink
text: I really love the show more and more… Yoongi has such a way of putting people at ease and drawing them out of their comfort zone. The show has also allowed people to see a side of him that many probably never knew existed. I do believe, as he says, the older he’s gotten the more settled and unguarded he has become. It was actually quite touching to hear how his mother and father were so emotional when he was working on the album. For whatever reason I have just always had in my head that his parents were A little harsh, and a little cold with him. I know in the beginning they did not support him but I think now of course all is well. I look forward to each episode of his show, because not only do we get discover the character of his guests, but we also get glimpses of little layers of him as well. He always tells us something different in his stories. I really admire and respect him so much, not only as an artist, but in the way he thinks as a person. It is easy to see why all seven members get along so well, and are truly brothers to one another. Each one of them are really completely different, yet their personalities really have mashed into one, and I really can’t imagine one without the other… Kind of like their DNA choreography chain. I look forward to his future episodes, and hope we get many more before his time to leave for duty.

author: @jess7613
text: There is something so endlessly endearing about such genuine conversations like this. Being a similar age and mindset to Yoongi, I feel so relieved watching these kinds of conversations. I don't have my life figured out, but I am learning more and more about life and people and growth everyday. Living with a calm and steadiness, but also reclaiming passion and drive and dreams. I genuinely can't thank Yoongi, BTS, and the Suchwita guests enough. Growing up is confusing and challenging but it's also a gift. To grow old, to continue to learn, to love and to lose. If anything, I have learned over the past few years, it's a true blessing to be an ARMY. Because I have gained so much since that fateful day. And Yoongi, I think you are strong. We all have strength and weaknesses. It's how we choose to overcome our own challenges is what makes true strength. Strength is also gentleness, tenderness. You and the guys and all ARMY who read this have such immense strength. I am so proud of you all. In a way, perceived weakness is strength too.

text: I have truly enjoyed all the Suchwita episodes. But this one and the one with RM when he divulges his major challenges in composing his 3rd part documentary and album truly reveal an amazing introspective, insightful, sensitive to almost painful levels and deeply intelligent AND high EQ person who doesn't fear increasingly revealing more of his authentic person. I also feel that the North American solo tour he has just completed with tremendous success which possibly surprised him above his expectations, has opened a dormant compartment in his soul permitting him to 'feel soft' and express his vulnerability in ways he has not done before. This has been a poignant moment in getting to know Yoongi more deeply. I feel he would make a great youth counsellor for South Koreans. He is de facto accomplishing this not only through his musical compositions but increasingly and with greater freedom in his varied public showings now that the band is temporarily on hiatus. I am so proud of these 7 wonderful boys-turned-men developing into remarkably sensitive authentic adults without the negative trappings of celebrity that are such a staple of most celebrities both in the West as well as in Asian countries (I'm thinking more of the Chinese and Indian 'stars').

author: @Karin_Allen
text: Imagine what it must have been like for Lee Na Young, not going on a talk show for ten years - and then choosing to promote her new drama with an interview. She seems like a gentle, sensitive person, and I know she put a lot of thought into which show to go on. I'm sure she knew what Suga was really like, and that he'd be a kindred spirit for her, which he absolutely was. He really knows how to put his guests at ease, and he genuinely cares about them. Ohh, the look on his face when she was talking about her dog! 😢

author: @cornsaladbts5811
text: I agree.  I'm sure that these types of interviews/variety shows are stressful, as you never know when a surprise question or topic may come up that you either don't want to discuss or could be taken out of context in a negative way.  This was more of a conversation, and there weren't any games or "gotcha" questions.  Yoongi is really a skilled interviewer, and he puts people at ease...and I also love that he answers his own question first to give the other person either time to think about what they want to say OR to simply react to his answer if they don't want to provide anything about themselves.  He is a genuine and lovely person, truly.

author: @TallieRS2378
text:
I enjoyed this episode. It was really refreshing. It is true, seeing people, celebrity or not, be their authentic self is amazing. As much as I love BTS music collectively and individually, what ultimately drew me in as a fan were the times they were just being themselves. Watching Run BTS, watching clips of old concerts where the members are just interacting with each other, the vlives/weverse lives and interviews, behind the scenes of music videos, were all moments we got to see BTS as Kim Namjoon, Kim Seokjin, Min Yoongi, Jung Hoseok, Park  Jimin, Kim Taehyung and Jeon Jungkook and not their personas. I love seeing those moments.

Hope this series can continue even after they all return from their enlistment.

author: @janethrosales5157
text:
Ehhh
Eres baby army, has visto las entrevistas y los viajes de cada miembro?
Los miembros toman la mayoría de las decisiones sobre cómo hacer sus actividades individuales.Estan cumpliendo durante el periodo de descanso como grupo, sus deseos individuales.
A ellos no les interesa tener éxito como artistas individuales sino que quieren experimentar cosas nuevas para volver con mejor música como grupo.
Por ejemplo: Suga decidió hacer este programa especial para que los otros miembros promocionarán sus álbumes individuales, y eso es lógico porque bts generalmente crea su propio contenido de comunicacion con el público( durante su carrera de 10 años casi nunca han ido a programas coreanos para promocionarse).
Ejemplo2: Suga decidió hacer el tour d-day por cuenta propia( tiene muchas canciones para hacerlo) en representación del grupo que cancelaron el tour mundial por la pandemia.Por otro: RM decidió por cuenta propia hacer un concierto pequeño, frente solo 200 personas.
Lo siento, pero si eres army tu comentario está muy fuera de lugar!
